      "writtenOn": "2019-09-20T11:52:46Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Responses inline.\n\n\u003e Thanks for explaining in person.\n\u003e \n\u003e I agree that using only firestore.NewModified* with the scheduling process won\u0027t work.\n\u003e \n\u003e IIUC, all non-test callers of firestore.NewDB* are specifying a ModifiedData, so it\u0027s fine with me if you submit as-is.\n\u003e \n\u003e I think there is still a problem with calling TrackModifiedTasks from both PutTasks and from the NewModifiedTasks goroutine, since we could get outdated data. The addition of modifiedData.ts in task_scheduler/go/db/modified/modified_data.go does not really solve the problem, since there\u0027s no guarantee that we\u0027ll refresh the outdated data before GetModifiedTasks is called. I can think of two ways to handle this:\n\u003e  a. In taskCache.insertOrUpdateTask in task_scheduler/go/db/cache/cache.go, ignore the new task if old.DbModified is newer. (And same for jobs.) (If there are other uses of GetModifiedTasks, we\u0027d need the same logic there.)\n\u003e  b. Don\u0027t clear modifiedData.ts in GetModified*. Periodically clear out any timestamps that are \u003e N minutes old. This is a bit more complicated, but it\u0027s a fix in only one spot.\n\u003e \n\nSo yeah, the thing I should\u0027ve made clearer is that the behavior of GetModifiedTasks has changed in this CL[*], and it may now return duplicated or outdated information.  I think this is okay as long as it\u0027s handled both internally in ModifiedData and by the clients.  I\u0027ve written the code to update TaskCache and JobCache, but it apparently didn\u0027t make its way to this CL...\n\n[*] Actually, I think we might already have this behavior with the PubSub ModifiedData, if less severe/frequent.\n\n\u003e For tests, IMO:\n\u003e  A. Scheduling-related tests should create a firestore.NewDB with modified.NewModifiedData() to mirror what we do in production. (Scheduling currently relies on Put* arguments immediately appearing in GetModified* results.) \n\nThe scheduling tests currently use the in-memory DB implementation with the vanilla modified.ModifiedData.  Do we need to switch to Firestore?  These tests are already slow, and adding Firestore to the mix would make them a lot slower.\n\n\u003e  B. We should probably test the firestore DB with modified.NewModifiedData() using the test helpers in task_scheduler/go/db/testutil.go, since this is the setup in production.\n\u003e  C. Additionally, IWBN to test the firestore DB with firestore.NewModified* using the test helpers in task_scheduler/go/db/testutil.go.\n\nSo I\u0027ve done (C) in this CL.  My plan is to update the clients to the new ModifiedData immediately afterward, verify that they\u0027re working as expected, and then update Task Scheduler itself.  (B) will no longer apply at that point.  Do we need to bother with tests for it?",
